{{technique}}

A '''rolling boil''' (also '''roiling boil''') is when a liquid is [[Cookbook:Boiling|boiled]] rapidly with lots of bubbling. This requires much more energy than [[Cookbook:Simmering|simmering]], and is often discouraged because it can break up or alter the shape of ingredients, whereas simmering will keep the ingredients whole. 

Some recipes require a rolling boil for the entire cooking period. Typically, however, recipes will specify that the liquid is brought to a rolling boil, then reduced to a simmer for the remainder of the cooking period.

