This section provides that, except where expressly provided elsewhere in the Taxes Acts, the profits of a [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Schedule A]] business are computed in the same way as the profits of a trade are computed for the purposes of [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 18 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Case I of Schedule D]].

The following sections therefore apply to the calculation of profits under Schedule A in the same way as they apply to the calculation of profits under Schedule D:

The following provisions apply in accordance with subsection (1)-

*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 87 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 72]] (apportionment); 
*the provisions of Chapter V of Part IV (computational provisions relating to the Schedule D charge), except as mentioned below; 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 577 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 577]] (business entertainment expenses); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 577A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 577A]] (expenditure involving crime); 
*Sections [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 579 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|579]] and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 580 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|580]] (redundancy payments); 
*Section [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 588 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|588]] (training courses for employees); 
*Section [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 589A of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|589A]] (counselling services for employees); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 73 of the Finance Act 1988|Section 73(2)]] of the Finance Act 1988 (consideration for restrictive undertakings); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 43 of the Finance Act 1989|Section 43]] of the Finance Act 1989 (deductions in respect of certain emoluments); 
*Sections [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 42 of the Finance Act 1998|42]] and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 46 of the Finance Act 1998|46(1) and (2)]] of the Finance Act 1998 (provisions as to computation of profits and losses).
*Sections [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 196 of the Finance Act 2004||196]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 196A of the Finance Act 2004|196A]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 197 of the Finance Act 2004|197]],  [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 198 of the Finance Act 2004|198]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 199 of the Finance Act 2004|199]] and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 200 of the Finance Act 2004|200]] of the Finance Act 2004 (registered pension schemes); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 246 of the Finance Act 2004|Section 246]] of the Finance Act 2004 (employer-financed retirement benefits schemes).

[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 74 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 74(1)(d) ICTA]] (disallowance of provisions for future repairs) applies in relation to a Schedule A business as if the reference to premises occupied for the purposes of the trade were to premises held for the purposes of the Schedule A business.

The following provisions that do apply for Schedule D purposes do not, however, apply for Schedule A:

*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 87 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 87]] (treatment of premiums taxed as rent), and 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 98 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 98]] (tied premises: receipts and expenses treated as those of trade).

Part 1 of [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Schedule 22 to the Finance Act 2001|Schedule 22 to the Finance Act 2001]] (deduction for capital expenditure on remediation of contaminated land) applies in accordance with subsection (1), and the other Parts of that Schedule (further provision as to relief for remediation of contaminated land) have effect in relation to a Schedule A business in accordance with their provisions. 

[[Category:Taxation in the United Kingdom]]

This section lists some further provisions that apply to a [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 15 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Schedule A]] business in the same way as they apply to a trade:

*Sections [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 103 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|103]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 104 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|104]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 105 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|105]], [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 106 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|106]] and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 110 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|110]] (post-cessation receipts and expenses, etc.); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 337 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|Section 337(1)]] (effect of company beginning or ceasing to carry on trade); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 401 of the Income and Corporation Taxes Act 1988|section 401(1)]] (pre-trading expenditure); 
*[[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Section 64 of the Finance Act 2002|Section 64]] of and [[Taxation in the United Kingdom/Legislation/Schedule 22 to the Finance Act 2002|Schedule 22]] to the Finance Act 2002 (change of accounting basis).

